00:05:05.690 --> 00:05:07.510
What about the link between atopy and

00:05:07.510 --> 00:05:09.790
autism spectrum disorder?

00:05:09.790 --> 00:05:12.460
I haven't seen evidence
that really convinces me

00:05:12.460 --> 00:05:16.270
that atopy predisposes to
autism spectrum disorder.

00:05:16.270 --> 00:05:18.560
There are some studies
that propose a link,

00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:20.750
but I didn't think the
data were very convincing.

00:05:20.750 --> 00:05:22.240
They're both extremely common,

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:25.420
and just because they're
together doesn't mean

00:05:25.420 --> 00:05:28.270
they're causative, one is
causative to the other.

00:05:28.270 --> 00:05:30.280
What we do know is that children who have

00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:33.260
autism spectrum disorder
and then are sleep deprived

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:34.900
because of their atopic derma can make

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:36.020
their behavioral problems worse,

00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:38.910
and that's true in all
children, of course.

00:05:38.910 --> 00:05:40.540
So we don't know whether atopic dermatitis

00:05:40.540 --> 00:05:41.900
is more prevalent in this population.

00:05:41.900 --> 00:05:43.347
There's some studies that say it is

00:05:43.347 --> 00:05:44.610
and others that say it isn't,

00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:46.903
so that's an open question at this point.

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:50.460
The tactile sensory
dysfunction, of course,

00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:54.220
exacerbates the itch,
the perception of itch,

00:05:54.220 --> 00:05:57.910
the experience of itch, and the
behavioral response to itch.

00:05:57.910 --> 00:06:02.040
So where one child might rub
their skin, my patient here,

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:05.820
like many patients with
developmental disability

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:08.020
tend to pick and dig at the skin,

00:06:08.020 --> 00:06:11.420
which is much more hard
to heal and hard to treat.

00:06:11.420 --> 00:06:14.130
It can increase agitation,
increase, of course,

00:06:14.130 --> 00:06:15.890
sleep disruption, which also can increase

00:06:15.890 --> 00:06:18.780
behavioral problems, and then
you will get super infections,

00:06:18.780 --> 00:06:22.030
so our friend here had nafcillin sensitive

00:06:22.030 --> 00:06:25.070
staph aureus infection that I cultured,

00:06:25.070 --> 00:06:27.810
and then worked with the
parents to eliminate that.

00:06:27.810 --> 00:06:29.570
That did help the eczema as well.

00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:30.930
Parents are already overwhelmed.

00:06:30.930 --> 00:06:32.700
You saw that diagram that Noemi showed

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:34.430
with all the things they have to do,

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:36.210
and here is this chronic skin problem

00:06:36.210 --> 00:06:40.140
that adds 45 minutes a day to the care.

00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:42.990
So I try to make it easy
for them and for the child,

00:06:42.990 --> 00:06:46.430
who may resist all topical
applications of any kind,

00:06:46.430 --> 00:06:48.630
and Noemi mentioned that as well.

00:06:48.630 --> 00:06:51.560
I'm asking them to use
greasy, thick moisturizers.

00:06:51.560 --> 00:06:54.160
It is not a pleasant sensation,
especially the older kids

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:56.930
really resist it, so I
work with the families,

00:06:56.930 --> 00:07:00.130
I compromise on my
ointments, and I compromise

00:07:00.130 --> 00:07:03.440
and allow them to use creams,
and if I have to, lotions,

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:04.780
which are much easier to put on

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:07.600
and much less effective
at treating the dry skin,

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:09.220
but I do believe that I need to make

00:07:09.220 --> 00:07:12.100
the whole situation palatable and workable

00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:14.240
and practical for the family.

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:16.520
I will tend to use a
stronger topical steroid

00:07:16.520 --> 00:07:19.290
once a day instead of a
mid-potency topical steroid

00:07:19.290 --> 00:07:21.310
twice a day, that's another compromise.

00:07:21.310 --> 00:07:23.820
I'll use a cream and
I'll go up a class or two

00:07:23.820 --> 00:07:26.480
on my topical steroid
strength in order to have

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:29.260
this be a bedtime routine
after the bath or shower

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:30.540
instead of having the family having to

00:07:30.540 --> 00:07:31.820
deal with this in the morning,

00:07:31.820 --> 00:07:34.680
trying to get the kid
out the door to school.

00:07:34.680 --> 00:07:36.650
We all know how hard that is.

00:07:36.650 --> 00:07:39.230
Then remember that topical
steroids do come in gels

00:07:39.230 --> 00:07:41.110
and solutions for the scalp.

00:07:41.110 --> 00:07:43.110
Solutions that are alcohol based can sting

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:44.440
and the child may resist them,

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:47.780
but gels tend to be not as
stingy, so remember that.

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:49.820
You can look up and see if there's a gel

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:53.160
that you can use in
your pharmacy formulary.

00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:55.010
You work with the parents,
and the primary care

00:07:55.010 --> 00:07:56.820
rely on you to also work with the parents

00:07:56.820 --> 00:08:00.080
to work with the child's personality,

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:02.320
temperament, and behavior issues.

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:04.476
Give them rewards for doing the skin care,

00:08:04.476 --> 00:08:07.290
and then if it's a
teenager who wants to use

00:08:07.290 --> 00:08:10.430
the smelly skin care products
that Noemi mentioned,

00:08:10.430 --> 00:08:14.170
I particularly will mention
Axe, which the boys love.

00:08:14.170 --> 00:08:16.210
Try to just keep those
products out of the house

00:08:16.210 --> 00:08:19.163
so the kids can't use them,
because they're very irritating.

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:22.010
Let's talk about itch.

00:08:22.010 --> 00:08:26.150
How can we break the itch/scratch/dig/pick

00:08:26.150 --> 00:08:28.560
infection cycle in our patients?

00:08:28.560 --> 00:08:31.590
I address staph
superinfection aggressively.

00:08:31.590 --> 00:08:33.630
Again, I like to apologize to Brian Lee

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:37.690
who is our infectious disease
specialist in our hospital

00:08:37.690 --> 00:08:39.540
who's always trying to get
us not to use antibiotics.

00:08:39.540 --> 00:08:41.130
I get that, and I try really hard not to,

00:08:41.130 --> 00:08:44.300
but sometimes you just have
to use systemic antibiotics.

00:08:44.300 --> 00:08:47.520
The amount of staph on the
skin overwhelms bleach baths,

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:49.143
in order to get the eczema under control.

00:08:49.143 --> 00:08:52.050
I do culture because the patients I see

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:54.430
are referred and severe, and I need data,

00:08:54.430 --> 00:08:56.540
so I do tend to culture
them more than you would

00:08:56.540 --> 00:08:59.190
and direct the staph
infection systemic therapy

00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:02.300
toward MSSA, MRSA, et cetera.

00:09:02.300 --> 00:09:03.770
Phototherapy is a tool that

00:09:03.770 --> 00:09:05.130
I'm trying to start at Children's.

00:09:05.130 --> 00:09:05.963
I have a grant in.

00:09:05.963 --> 00:09:07.210
Anybody who knows anybody on the

00:09:07.210 --> 00:09:09.450
President's Innovation
Fund grant committee?

00:09:09.450 --> 00:09:13.400
Can you wave to them, because
we really need phototherapy.

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:16.560
This is a health disparity
issue for our patients.

00:09:16.560 --> 00:09:18.380
What phototherapy does
for you is it drives

00:09:18.380 --> 00:09:20.960
the immune system out of the
skin and immediately helps

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:22.520
the itch, and it helps the skin heal

00:09:22.520 --> 00:09:24.630
in the case of atomic dermatitis.

00:09:24.630 --> 00:09:27.810
Systemic therapy such as
Dupilumad, as of two days ago,

00:09:27.810 --> 00:09:29.860
are now FDA approved
down to 12 years of age,

00:09:29.860 --> 00:09:31.890
so we're extremely excited about this,

00:09:31.890 --> 00:09:34.160
and it is a drug we can
use in this population.

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:35.660
It's not immuno suppressive

00:09:35.660 --> 00:09:38.070
like all of our other medications.

00:09:38.070 --> 00:09:40.480
Occlusion is great, but if you have a kid

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:42.040
who has sensory issues,
they are not going to

00:09:42.040 --> 00:09:44.520
want their legs wrapped,
but if you do have a kid

00:09:44.520 --> 00:09:46.810
who will tolerate it, you
can get these beautiful,

00:09:46.810 --> 00:09:50.240
colorful Coban wraps
or other brands online

00:09:50.240 --> 00:09:52.390
for pretty cheap in pretty colors,

00:09:52.390 --> 00:09:54.580
and you can wrap the
legs and keep the fingers

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:57.210
off the wounds and allow them to heal.

00:09:57.210 --> 00:09:59.030
You can also, for a localized lesion,

00:09:59.030 --> 00:10:01.610
use a Duoderm, which is a
venous stasis ulcer dressing,

00:10:01.610 --> 00:10:03.160
no stock in that company,

00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:07.260
or any kind of a stick
but not adhesive dressing

00:10:07.260 --> 00:10:10.133
wrapped with an Ace
bandage and then Tegaderm.

00:10:11.400 --> 00:10:13.380
Yesterday you hear a little bit how

00:10:13.380 --> 00:10:14.950
antihistamines, sedating antihistamines

00:10:14.950 --> 00:10:18.160
can be problematic in kids
with behavioral problems.

00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:21.260
I second that, and it can
lower seizure threshold,

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:22.690
but if they don't have those issues,

00:10:22.690 --> 00:10:25.638
they don't have paradoxical
reactions or seizure disorder,

00:10:25.638 --> 00:10:28.290
one per kilo hydroxyzine at bedtime

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:31.090
or Benadryl at bedtime can
really help during a flare.

00:10:31.090 --> 00:10:33.933
I don't use them chronically
unless I absolutely have to.

